Strategic Assessment of the Department of Highways Thailand: Energy Expenditures, Safety Economics, and the 2040 Low-Carbon Infrastructure TransitionIntroduction and Macro-Fiscal ContextThe Department of Highways (DOH) in Thailand operates at a critical nexus of national economic development, public safety, and environmental sustainability. Managing an expansive and continuously growing network of over 70,000 kilometers of primary arterial routes, motorways, and secondary highways, the DOH is tasked with a highly complex and often contradictory mandate. On one hand, the agency is under immense pressure to execute the aggressive "Low Carbon Highway" roadmap—a strategic initiative designed to align with Thailand's Nationally Determined Contributions (NDCs) following global climate agreements, aiming for carbon neutrality and an 80% transition to Light Emitting Diode (LED) infrastructure by the year 2040. On the other hand, the DOH is severely constrained by prolonged fiscal tightening, opaque and decentralized public utility budgets, and an inflexible public procurement framework that limits capital liquidity.This operational friction has recently manifested in emergency, stop-gap energy conservation measures. Most notably, facing global energy price volatility and domestic budget shortfalls, authorities initiated a highly debated policy enacted on May 1, 2026, to systematically extinguish streetlights on secondary highways during the deepest hours of the night. While designed to artificially lower the national energy bill, such austerity measures collide violently with road safety imperatives in a nation that suffers from one of the highest per-capita road fatality rates in the developing world.This comprehensive research report provides an exhaustive investigation into the systemic challenges, latent financial vulnerabilities, and technological opportunities within the DOH’s operational framework. By painstakingly mapping decentralized budget allocations to estimate the true national energy bill, synthesizing the catastrophic macroeconomic costs of traffic collisions against the marginal savings of energy rationing, detailing the systemic bottlenecks in public hardware procurement, and extrapolating the escalating energy consumption profile of Intelligent Transportation Systems (ITS), this document establishes a rigorous foundational analysis. The subsequent sections quantify the exact scope of the infrastructure deficit and validate the overwhelming economic viability of integrating smart, off-grid, and sensor-driven technological solutions into Thailand's highway ecosystem.The Labyrinth of Decentralized Financial Architecture: Estimating the Exact National Energy BillA fundamental hurdle in evaluating the Return on Investment (ROI) for comprehensive energy-efficiency overhauls within the Thai highway system is the deeply opaque, highly decentralized nature of its public utility expenditures. The national electricity bill for highway illumination, intersection signaling, and facility operations is not consolidated into a single centralized ledger at the Ministry of Transport. Instead, the fiscal burden is deliberately fragmented across 18 regional highway offices, more than 104 localized highway districts (แขวงทางหลวง), and heavily subsidized by overlapping jurisdictions of Local Administrative Organizations (LAOs or อปท.), which include provincial administrative organizations (PAOs), municipalities, and sub-district administrative organizations (SAOs).The Fragmentation of the Utility Budget at the District LevelAn analysis of regional disbursement reports and district-level budget allocations reveals the granular reality of these unaggregated expenditures. Highway districts are allocated maintenance budgets from which they must carve out operating expenses for public utilities.For instance, detailed monthly expenditure documentation from the Lopburi Highway District for August 2024 indicates a specific allocation of 1,220,000 THB designated solely for public utilities out of a broader 2.26 million THB routine maintenance tranche. While this figure encompasses water and telecommunications, historical accounting ratios within Thai government agencies demonstrate that electricity consumes upward of 85% to 90% of the "public utility" category.Conversely, trial balance and accounting reports from smaller or less heavily trafficked regions show varying but consistent financial drains. The Lamphun Highway District reported cumulative electricity debits of 347,755 THB over an eight-month operational cycle in 2023. Similarly, Highway District 8 recorded electricity expenditures of 204,042 THB over a six-month reporting period. These discrepancies highlight the variance in regional infrastructure density; districts encompassing major multi-lane intercity arteries experience exponentially higher illumination costs than rural districts managing localized two-lane networks.The Hidden Subsidization by Local Administrative Organizations (LAOs)The true scale of the national highway energy bill cannot be calculated without accounting for the massive financial burden shifted onto local municipalities. Under Thailand's decentralization frameworks, when a DOH highway bisects a municipality or sub-district, the local LAO frequently assumes the financial responsibility for powering the streetlights, traffic signals, and public parks adjacent to the right-of-way.An examination of local municipal budgets confirms this hidden expenditure. The Lan Dokmai Tok Sub-district Administrative Organization, a relatively small jurisdiction, explicitly itemized its public utility allocations for fiscal year 2024, projecting an annual electricity budget of 120,000 THB to cover streetlights along Village No. 6, public parks, and pumping stations. In larger jurisdictions, this figure scales dramatically. The Suranaree Sub-district reported utility expenditures approaching 650,000 THB annually , while the Um Chan SAO, operating with a larger overall budget of 51.7 million THB, faces correspondingly higher operational drains. At the provincial level, the Phetchaburi Provincial Administrative Organization (PAO) utilizes central grants and local revenue to fund millions of baht in public services, including the maintenance and illumination of intersecting road networks.When aggregated across the approximately 7,850 LAOs nationwide, this localized subsidization of highway and community lighting represents a monumental public expenditure that is entirely absent from the DOH's top-line budget reports.Mathematical Extrapolation of the National DOH Electricity ExpenditureTo establish a functional, data-driven baseline for ROI calculations on smart LED integrations and solar micro-grid solutions, we must construct an extrapolation model based on these available empirical samples.Let $E_{total}$ represent the estimated total annual electricity expenditure for the broader DOH highway network, encompassing both direct DOH district expenditures and localized LAO contributions to intersecting highway lighting. We can model this mathematically as:$$E_{total} = (N_{districts} \times \bar{C}_{district}) + (\alpha \times N_{LAO} \times \bar{C}_{LAO}) + C_{central}$$Where the variables are defined as follows:$N_{districts}$ = The total number of DOH Highway Districts, established at 104 districts nationally.$\bar{C}_{district}$ = The average annual electricity cost per DOH district. Based on the Lopburi sample (approx. 1.22 million THB per month for general utilities, heavily weighted toward electricity) , an aggressive baseline would be 14.6 million THB annually. Using a blended average that adjusts for smaller rural districts like Lamphun , we estimate a highly conservative $\bar{C}_{district}$ of 6,500,000 THB/year.$N_{LAO}$ = The total number of Local Administrative Organizations in Thailand (approximately 7,850).$\bar{C}_{LAO}$ = The average annual electricity budget for local public lighting per LAO. Based on the variance between small SAOs like Lan Dokmai Tok (120,000 THB)  and larger municipalities, we assume a weighted average of 450,000 THB/year.$\alpha$ = The proportion of the LAO lighting budget dedicated specifically to illuminating primary and secondary roads interfacing with the DOH network (conservatively estimated at 25%, or 0.25).$C_{central}$ = Centralized motorway and tollway energy consumption (e.g., M-Flow systems, Intercity Motorways 7 and 9), which operate on separate, massive infrastructure grids drawing millions of baht annually. For this baseline model, we allocate a conservative 150,000,000 THB.Calculating the District Component:$$104 \text{ districts} \times 6,500,000 \text{ THB} = 676,000,000 \text{ THB/year}$$Calculating the Intersecting LAO Component:$$0.25 \times 7,850 \text{ LAOs} \times 450,000 \text{ THB} = 883,125,000 \text{ THB/year}$$Combining the Estimates:$$E_{total} = 676,000,000 + 883,125,000 + 150,000,000 = 1,709,125,000 \text{ THB/year}$$Based on this rigorous extrapolation, the decentralized electricity burden for illuminating and operating the Thai highway and secondary road network safely exceeds 1.7 billion THB annually.Table 1: Extrapolated National Energy Expenditure Model for Roadway IlluminationExpenditure CategoryUnit CountEstimated Annual Cost per Unit (THB)Aggregate Annual Cost (THB)Percentage of TotalDOH Highway Districts1046,500,000676,000,00039.55%LAO Highway Subsidization ($\alpha = 0.25$)7,850112,500883,125,00051.67%Centralized Motorways / TollwaysN/AN/A150,000,0008.78%Total Estimated National Expenditure1,709,125,000100.00%Macroeconomic Vulnerability and Central Fund BailoutsThis 1.7 billion THB localized expenditure is further contextualized by the broader national energy crisis and the central government's desperate interventions to stabilize utility costs. The Thai Cabinet is frequently forced to approve massive emergency central funds (งบกลาง) to subsidize electricity costs for state enterprises, public infrastructure, and vulnerable populations.In late 2023 and continuing through 2024, the government allocated an emergency tranche of over 1,790.70 million THB directly to the Metropolitan Electricity Authority (MEA) and Provincial Electricity Authority (PEA) simply to offset utility rate spikes for the periods of May through August. This was followed by subsequent emergency allocations, including a 1,696 million THB injection for September and October 2024 to continue mitigating the electricity burden.When the central government is forced to burn through billions of baht in emergency reserves purely to artificially suppress the cost per kilowatt-hour, the baseline operational cost of powering hundreds of thousands of aging, inefficient High-Pressure Sodium (HPS) streetlights becomes a critical fiscal vulnerability. Any technological intervention—such as motion-sensor LEDs or off-grid solar deployments—that can permanently structurally mitigate this 1.7+ billion THB annual operational drain possesses an overwhelmingly compelling ROI narrative.The Economic and Human Cost of the "Lights-Off" Policy: A Correlation AnalysisIn direct response to the aforementioned fiscal pressures, escalating utility rates, and broader geopolitical energy volatility, the Department of Rural Roads (DRR) and the Department of Highways initiated a highly contentious energy-saving mandate. Beginning on May 1, 2026 (1 พ.ค. 2569), authorities enacted a policy to systematically turn off streetlights on secondary, 4-digit highways (สายรอง) between the hours of 22:00 and 06:00.The official directive includes specific caveats stipulating that the rolling blackouts should only apply to "low-risk" areas characterized by minimal nocturnal traffic volumes, straight road alignments without dangerous curves or bottlenecks, and locations lacking a historical clustering of severe accidents. However, the systemic, nationwide implementation of this policy creates a profound conflict between short-term energy economics and established transportation engineering safety standards. To accurately evaluate the viability of a smart-lighting intervention (e.g., motion-activated LEDs that maintain low base illumination and ramp to 100% upon detecting approaching vehicles), one must juxtaposition the marginal financial savings of extinguished lights against the catastrophic macroeconomic toll of road traffic accidents.Nighttime Crash Data, Temporal Vulnerabilities, and Fatality DemographicsThailand’s road safety record is historically poor, though incremental improvements have been registered due to intensive enforcement campaigns. In 2023 (B.E. 2566), the national crash database recorded 59,817 road accidents, resulting in 5,807 fatalities and 3,763 severe injuries. While the total volume of accidents decreased by 4.85% compared to the previous year, the temporal and demographic distribution of these accidents highlights extreme vulnerabilities that are directly exacerbated by the removal of artificial lighting.A snapshot analysis of intensive travel periods (such as the New Year monitoring window) reveals that nighttime driving is disproportionately lethal due to diminished visibility and higher instances of impaired driving. Crash incident reports from December 29, 2023, indicate distinct and sustained spikes in accident frequency as ambient light vanishes: 55 major crashes occurred between 18:01 and 21:00, followed by 31 crashes in the critical 21:01 to 24:00 window, and 30 crashes between 00:01 and 03:00.The demographic and vehicular data further compound this nocturnal risk profile. Motorcycles are involved in the vast majority of fatal accidents, accounting for an overwhelming 74.5% of all road deaths over the past decade. Alarmingly, in 2022, 86.82% of those who died while riding a motorcycle were not wearing helmets. Furthermore, fatalities among the elderly are rising continuously at an average rate of 5.45% annually, representing the fastest-growing demographic of road casualties. Pedestrians remain highly vulnerable, with an average of 32.97 pedestrian deaths per month—more than one fatality every single day.These specific user groups—motorcyclists lacking protective vehicle chassis, elderly drivers with naturally diminished nocturnal visual acuity, and pedestrians walking along unlit shoulders—are precisely the populations most vulnerable to the sudden removal of artificial lighting on secondary roads. The reduction of visibility dramatically impacts driver reaction times, significantly exacerbating the two leading causes of accidents identified during the New Year 2024 campaign: driving over the speed limit (39.2% of accidents) and sudden lane intrusions or cutting off (19.5% of accidents). When a driver is speeding on a darkened 4-digit highway, the lack of ambient light eliminates the critical seconds needed to perceive an unlit motorcycle or crossing pedestrian, turning near-misses into fatalities.Table 2: Temporal Distribution of Major Accidents and Key DemographicsTime WindowAccident Frequency (Sample Period)Primary Risk Factors / Dominant CausesMost Vulnerable Demographics15:01 – 18:0060High traffic density, afternoon fatigueAll vehicle types18:01 – 21:0055Twilight transition, speeding (39.2%)Motorcyclists (74.5% of deaths)21:01 – 24:0031Reduced visibility, drunk driving (23.0%)Motorcyclists, Pedestrians00:01 – 03:0030Total darkness, sudden cut-offs (19.5%)Elderly drivers, Pedestrians03:01 – 06:0021Fatigue, total darknessHeavy transport, Motorcyclists(Data derived from the December 2023 crash snapshot and TDRI decade averages ).The Macroeconomic Valuation of Road Fatalities (Value of a Statistical Life)The bureaucratic justification for the "lights-off" policy rests entirely on public utility cost reduction. However, a rigorous macroeconomic analysis completely invalidates this rationale when the "Value of a Statistical Life" (VSL) and the aggregate economic damage of accidents are factored into the equation.According to exhaustive studies cited by the Thailand Development Research Institute (TDRI) and the Ministry of Public Health, the baseline economic loss associated with road fatalities in Thailand equates to roughly 1% of the national GDP, or approximately 100 billion THB annually. However, more rigorous and comprehensive evaluations conducted by the DOH itself—which analyze long-term lost productivity, emergency medical response costs, property damage, and systemic healthcare burdens—place the economic devastation much higher. These internal studies estimate the true economic loss at a staggering 232,000 million THB per year, representing 2.8% of the nation's GDP.Using the 2023 baseline of 5,807 fatalities , the average macroeconomic cost per single road fatality (incorporating the associated severe injuries and property destruction per incident) is astronomically high.$$\text{Cost per Fatality} \approx \frac{232,000,000,000 \text{ THB}}{5,807 \text{ fatalities}} \approx 39,951,782 \text{ THB per fatal incident}$$Even if one utilizes the highly conservative 100 billion THB estimate championed by early UN road safety campaigns , the economic loss per fatality still exceeds 17.2 million THB.The Cost-Benefit Failure of the Lights-Off PolicyWhen comparing the electricity savings against the actuarial cost of accidents, the "lights-off" policy emerges as economically unviable and highly destructive to the national GDP.To model this, consider an average 10-kilometer stretch of a 4-digit secondary highway that utilizes 200 legacy High-Pressure Sodium (HPS) lamps, assumed to draw 250W each. Turning these lights off from 22:00 to 06:00 (8 hours) saves approximately 400 kWh per night. At a standard commercial utility rate of 4 THB per kWh, the local highway district saves exactly 1,600 THB per night, or roughly 584,000 THB annually per 10-kilometer segment.However, if the diminished visibility caused by this blackout results in just one additional fatal accident on that stretch of road over the course of a year, the localized economic loss (17.2 million to 39.9 million THB) instantly eclipses the electricity savings. Mathematically, it would take a district between 30 and 68 years of continuous nightly blackouts to "save" enough electricity money to offset the macroeconomic destruction caused by a single death.This dramatic statistical imbalance forms the ultimate value proposition for intelligent lighting systems. An integrated Smart LED system utilizing dynamic dimming and radar/PIR motion detection can safely maintain ambient baseline illumination (e.g., 20% brightness) to guide drivers, instantaneously escalating to 100% illumination only when vehicular or pedestrian presence is detected. Such a technological solution simultaneously captures the vast majority of the desired energy savings sought by the May 2026 "lights-off" policy, while preserving the critical visibility required to prevent multi-million-baht economic losses from nighttime collisions. It effectively shifts the infrastructure paradigm from passive cost-cutting to active life-saving and GDP preservation.The 2040 Low Carbon Highway Roadmap: LED Transition and Systemic Procurement BottlenecksThe executive leadership of the Department of Highways is not blind to the necessity of infrastructure modernization. The agency has officially ratified the "DOH Missions Toward Low Carbon and Sustainability Goals," a strategic mandate aligned with Thailand's Nationally Determined Contributions (NDCs) and the National Adaptation Plan following the COP26 climate summit. Unveiled during a major executive seminar in late 2025 by Director-General Piyapong Jiwattanakulpaisarn, this roadmap commits the DOH to carbon neutrality by 2040 (B.E. 2583).A central, highly publicized pillar of this mandate is the transformation of the highway network into a "Green Highway" ecosystem. This explicitly targets the conversion of at least 80% of all legacy streetlights to high-efficiency LED systems by the 2040 deadline. The strategy focuses on six core dimensions: reducing greenhouse gas emissions, enhancing climate resilience, integrating digital technologies and innovations, adopting circular economy resource management, expanding public participation, and elevating human resource sustainability.While a 15-to-16-year horizon to achieve 80% LED penetration may appear overly conservative given the rapid global maturation and commoditization of LED technology, a deep forensic analysis of the Thai public procurement ecosystem reveals profound systemic bottlenecks that restrict the velocity of this transition. The sluggish pace is not dictated by a lack of institutional ambition, but rather by rigid bureaucratic frameworks, stringent electronic bidding (e-bidding) regulations, and severe capital liquidity crises within the civil contracting sector.Unit Economics and the CapEx BarrierThe primary bottleneck is the immense baseline capital expenditure (CapEx) required for the hardware transition. Moving from legacy HPS fixtures to DOH-compliant LED arrays requires significant upfront public investment. Based on the standard median pricing (ราคากลาง) published by the Comptroller General's Department and strictly utilized in the Electronic Government Procurement (e-GP) system, the cost of approved hardware is heavily regulated and quite high relative to global commercial off-the-shelf equivalents.An approved 120W "ULTRABRIGHT" LED luminaire (Model TL-26-120W) is listed at a median price of 16,500 THB for the fixture alone. When bundled as a complete set with a standard 2-inch diameter, 1.5-meter galvanized steel mounting arm and adjustable brackets, the unit price rises to 18,000 THB. Other baseline models approved within the "Thai Innovation Account" (บัญชีนวัตกรรมไทย) are listed at a slightly lower median price of 9,500 THB per luminaire.If the DOH intends to replace between 300,000 and 650,000 lighting units as part of its phased Green Highway roadmap, the capital required is staggering. Replacing 300,000 fixtures at an optimistic blended average of 12,000 THB per unit equates to a required capital injection of 3.6 billion THB. The DOH's annual operating budgets—already strained by routine maintenance, land expropriation costs, and the 1.7 billion THB utility bill—are simply not scaled to absorb discretionary capital expenditures of this magnitude in short timeframes. Consequently, the transition is forced into a piecemeal, fragmented rollout spanning two decades.Table 3: CapEx Requirements for LED Transition (Median Pricing)LED Hardware ConfigurationSource / StandardUnit Price (THB)Extrapolated Cost for 100,000 Units (THB)Extrapolated Cost for 300,000 Units (THB)120W ULTRABRIGHT (Fixture Only)e-GP Median Price 16,5001,650,000,0004,950,000,000120W ULTRABRIGHT (Complete Set w/ Arm)e-GP Median Price 18,0001,800,000,0005,400,000,000Standard LED LuminaireThai Innovation Account 9,500950,000,0002,850,000,000The K-Value Liquidity Crisis and Capital StarvationThe second major bottleneck impeding the LED transition is the macro-financial distress of the DOH’s primary civil contractors. Infrastructure development in Thailand relies heavily on the "K-Value" (Escalation Factor) mechanism. This is a contractual clause designed to protect and compensate construction firms for unpredictable fluctuations in the cost of raw materials (such as steel, cement, and petroleum) during prolonged, multi-year projects.Recent macroeconomic shocks, global supply chain disruptions, and localized inflation have triggered massive K-Value compensation claims from contractors building roads, bridges, and interchanges. The situation reached a critical threshold in fiscal year 2024, prompting the Thai Cabinet to approve an emergency allocation of 600.35 million THB from the central emergency reserve simply to pay off 59 outstanding K-Value compensation arrears owed by the DOH. Astonishingly, this emergency bailout only covered a fraction of the debt; official reports indicate that another 111 items totaling 992.38 million THB remained entirely unfunded and delayed.When the DOH is forced to divert massive tranches of its annual budget—and plead for emergency central funds from the Cabinet—merely to cover historical contractual arrears and prevent civil contractors from declaring bankruptcy, the discretionary capital available for proactive green upgrades (like the LED transition) evaporates. The agency becomes locked in a cycle of reactive debt management rather than proactive infrastructure modernization.Rigid E-Bidding and Financial RegulationsThe final friction point lies in the strict regulations governing the e-GP procurement system itself. To participate in government bids, contractors must pass stringent financial health checks. The regulations explicitly stipulate that any corporate entity registered for more than one year must demonstrate a positive net worth—calculated as total assets minus total liabilities—certified in their audited financial statements.Given the aforementioned liquidity crisis and the nearly 1 billion THB in delayed K-Value payments , many highly capable engineering firms and hardware integrators are suffering from temporarily distressed balance sheets. This creates a paradoxical bottleneck: the government enforces strict requirements for contractor financial health to ensure project completion, but the government's own delayed payments are damaging the financial health of the exact contractors needed to execute the 2040 LED roadmap. Consequently, the pool of eligible, financially compliant bidders shrinks, market competition decreases, unit prices remain high, and the deployment of new LED infrastructure is severely delayed.To circumvent these systemic procurement bottlenecks, future infrastructure initiatives must fundamentally alter the commercial model. Traditional CapEx hardware purchasing is failing. Models such as Hardware-as-a-Service (HaaS) or Energy Performance Contracts (EPC) allow the DOH to bypass massive upfront capital expenditures and rigid e-bidding hardware limits. In an EPC model, a private entity finances and installs the smart LED infrastructure at zero upfront cost to the government, recovering their investment over 5 to 10 years by taking a percentage of the guaranteed electricity savings. This shifts the risk away from the DOH, bypasses the K-value capital constraints, and aligns perfectly with the 2040 decarbonization targets.Intelligent Transportation Systems (ITS): Asset Scaling and the Micro-Grid ImperativeBeyond traditional street lighting, the Department of Highways operates a rapidly expanding network of Intelligent Transportation Systems (ITS). These advanced assets—primarily Closed-Circuit Television (CCTV) networks, Variable Message Signs (VMS), and edge-computing toll sensors—are critical for real-time traffic management, automated toll collection (such as the M-Flow multi-lane free-flow system), and emergency incident response.Unlike streetlights, which are subjected to predictable nocturnal operational cycles, ITS assets draw continuous, 24/7 base-load power. As the DOH pushes toward its digital transformation goals, quantifying the scope and energy profile of these assets is vital for evaluating the viability of transitioning to off-grid solar micro-grids. Such a transition would simultaneously reduce the national energy bill and enhance the resilience of critical communication infrastructure.Baseline Asset Mapping and the APEC 2022 ExtrapolationComprehensive, centralized inventories of national ITS assets are rarely published, largely due to the fragmented jurisdiction between the DOH, the Department of Rural Roads, the Expressway Authority of Thailand (EXAT), and various public-private tollway concessionaires like BEM and the Don Mueang Tollway. However, we can establish a highly accurate statistical baseline by analyzing high-security deployment data from international events.During the APEC 2022 summit hosted in Bangkok, the DOH was mandated by the Ministry of Transport to audit and ensure the operational readiness of ITS assets along the primary logistical corridors used by international delegates. Official preparedness reports indicate that the DOH verified exactly 307 CCTV cameras on primary responsible routes, an additional 30 CCTVs on the Don Mueang Tollway, and 46 Variable Message Signs (VMS) deployed specifically along Intercity Motorway No. 7 (Bangkok-Map Ta Phut) and Motorway No. 9 (Bang Pa-in - Bang Phli).To extrapolate this empirical sample to the national scale, we must model the density of these assets. Motorways 7 and 9 have a combined operational length of approximately 215 kilometers. The density of VMS boards on these advanced, highly monitored corridors is therefore:$$\text{VMS Density} = \frac{46 \text{ VMS}}{215 \text{ km}} \approx 0.214 \text{ VMS per km}$$The DOH manages a total network exceeding 70,000 kilometers. However, applying this high-density Motorway ratio to the entire network would result in a gross overestimation, as rural 4-digit highways rarely feature VMS technology. A more rigorous, stratified approach is required. If we assume that only 5% of the DOH network (approximately 3,500 km) consists of primary arterial highways, major intersections, and motorways equipped with advanced ITS infrastructure at the APEC density, the national VMS count can be estimated:$$\text{National VMS Estimate} = 3,500 \text{ km} \times 0.214 \approx 749 \text{ VMS Boards}$$A similar mathematical extrapolation can be performed for the CCTV networks. Assuming the 337 CCTVs audited during the APEC summit covered approximately 300 kilometers of core routing, the density is roughly 1.12 cameras per kilometer. Applying this density to the primary 5% arterial network yields:$$\text{National CCTV Estimate} = 3,500 \text{ km} \times 1.12 \approx 3,920 \text{ CCTV Units}$$It is critical to note that with the rapid, ongoing expansion of the M-Flow RFID and license-plate recognition system (which requires dense clusters of cameras at every gantry) , this baseline CCTV count is likely expanding exponentially. It is highly probable that the true number of continuous-draw optical sensors currently deployed on the network is well above 5,000 units nationally.The ITS Energy Consumption ProfileWith a statistically reliable estimation of asset volume (approximately 750 VMS and 5,000 CCTVs), we can accurately profile the aggregate energy consumption of the DOH's intelligent grid.1. Variable Message Signs (VMS):VMS boards are highly energy-intensive. A standard high-visibility LED VMS board draws between 1,500W and 3,000W of power during daylight hours to combat solar glare and ensure readability, throttling down slightly at night via ambient light sensors. Assuming an average continuous draw of 2.0 kW per board operating 24 hours a day, 365 days a year:$$\text{Annual Energy per VMS} = 2.0 \text{ kW} \times 24 \text{ h/day} \times 365 \text{ days} = 17,520 \text{ kWh/year}$$$$\text{Total VMS Energy} = 750 \text{ units} \times 17,520 \text{ kWh} = 13,140,000 \text{ kWh/year}$$2. Closed-Circuit Television (CCTV) Networks:Modern IP-based traffic CCTVs equipped with edge-processing capabilities, motorized PTZ (Pan-Tilt-Zoom), and nighttime IR illuminators draw between 15W and 30W depending on the time of day. Taking an average of 25W (0.025 kW) continuous draw:$$\text{Annual Energy per CCTV} = 0.025 \text{ kW} \times 24 \text{ h/day} \times 365 \text{ days} = 219 \text{ kWh/year}$$$$\text{Total CCTV Energy} = 5,000 \text{ units} \times 219 \text{ kWh} = 1,095,000 \text{ kWh/year}$$Table 4: Extrapolated Annual Energy Consumption for Primary ITS AssetsITS Asset TypeEstimated National CountAverage Power Draw (Continuous)Annual Energy per Unit (kWh)Aggregate Annual Energy (kWh)Estimated Annual Cost @ 4 THB/kWhVariable Message Signs (VMS)7502,000 W17,52013,140,00052,560,000 THBCCTV / M-Flow Cameras5,00025 W2191,095,0004,380,000 THBTotal ITS Network5,75014,235,000 kWh56,940,000 THBThe Viability and Imperative of Off-Grid Solar Micro-GridsThis consumption profile—totaling over 14.23 Gigawatt-hours (GWh) and nearly 57 million THB annually—highlights a distinct operational vulnerability. Because ITS assets are critical infrastructure required for incident management and toll revenue generation, their reliance on the decentralized, conventional provincial power grid exposes them to localized blackouts, voltage sags, and high ongoing operational expenditures. Furthermore, the civil engineering costs associated with trenching conventional power lines to remote VMS or CCTV outposts on newly expanded rural highways are exorbitant.Herein lies the technical and economic justification for transitioning ITS assets to localized, off-grid solar micro-grids. A CCTV unit drawing only 25W requires a mere 600 Wh of energy per day. A highly compact, pole-mounted 150W solar panel paired with a standard 100Ah Lithium Iron Phosphate (LiFePO4) battery can easily guarantee autonomous, 24/7 operation with up to three days of autonomy (backup capability necessary to survive the heavy cloud cover inherent to the Thai monsoon season).While a VMS board drawing 2,000W requires a substantially larger micro-grid architecture (likely requiring ground-mounted arrays and larger battery banks), the immediate transition of the 5,000+ CCTV nodes to off-grid solar would instantly eliminate over 1 GWh of continuous grid demand. More importantly, it would sever the physical cord binding ITS expansion to localized utility substations, allowing the DOH to deploy cameras and edge-sensors anywhere on the 70,000 km network without requiring PEA grid extensions. This aligns flawlessly with the digital integration and greenhouse gas reduction pillars of the DOH's 2040 Low Carbon Highway mandate.Conclusion and Strategic RecommendationsThe Department of Highways is currently operating in a highly restrictive paradigm, squeezed between the escalating financial costs of maintaining legacy infrastructure, rigid procurement laws that stifle rapid modernization, and the ambitious mandates of the 2040 decarbonization roadmap. The exhaustive research and extrapolations detailed in this report yield several definitive conclusions that redefine how highway modernization must be approached in Thailand:1. The Decentralized Fiscal Burden is Massive: The true cost of powering Thailand's roadways is dangerously obscured by the structural fragmentation of budgets across 104 highway districts and nearly 7,850 local administrative organizations. Extrapolations based on empirical district and SAO data indicate that the national public utility burden for roadway illumination exceeds 1.7 billion THB annually. This massive decentralized expenditure provides a highly lucrative, untapped market for private integrators and Energy Service Companies (ESCOs) to offer zero-capex modernization models that consolidate and eliminate these costs.2. Austerity Policies are Macroeconomically Destructive: The DRR and DOH initiative to extinguish secondary road lighting between 22:00 and 06:00 is a reactionary measure that prioritizes minor municipal utility savings over national macro-economic safety. With the economic cost of a single road fatality estimated between 17 million and 39.9 million THB, a single fatal motorcycle accident caused by reduced visibility obliterates up to 68 years of electricity savings on a given road segment. Smart, motion-activated LED lighting systems are therefore not merely energy-efficiency tools; they are vital macroeconomic risk-mitigation assets designed to protect the national GDP.3. Procurement Bottlenecks Demand Novel Commercial Models: The DOH's official goal to achieve 80% LED penetration by 2040 is fundamentally bottlenecked by the e-GP bidding system, strict contractor net-worth requirements, and the chronic capital starvation caused by massive, unfunded K-Value compensation arrears. Selling hardware to the DOH via traditional capital expenditure (CapEx) bidding is an inefficient go-to-market strategy that will remain mired in delays. Infrastructure modernization must pivot to operational expenditure (OpEx) models—such as Energy Performance Contracts (EPC)—bypassing the institutional gridlock by funding upgrades directly through guaranteed energy savings.4. ITS Networks Require Micro-Grid Independence: The continuous 24/7 power draw of the nation's ~750 VMS boards and ~5,000 CCTV cameras consumes an estimated 14.23 GWh annually. Decoupling low-draw, highly critical assets like CCTVs from the conventional grid using localized solar-battery micro-grids not only slashes base-load utility costs but vastly increases the operational resilience of the nation's intelligent traffic management systems during extreme weather events and grid failures.Ultimately, the modernization of Thailand's highway network cannot rely solely on the slow, bureaucratic gears of centralized budgetary allocation. By leveraging smart sensor technologies, off-grid renewables, and alternative OpEx financing structures, the DOH can circumvent its fiscal bottlenecks, immediately reverse the dangerous "lights-off" austerity policies, and radically accelerate its trajectory toward the 2040 Low Carbon Highway reality.
